docs.lead_paragraph: We published yesterday a voluminous personal correspondence between DANIEL E. SICKLES, Esq., our Secretary of Legation at London, and Mr. GEORGE PEABODY, the eminent American Banker of that city. Although it is not calculated to be very edifying or instructive, we trust it will be generally read:

docs.lead_paragraph: The Annual Address before the Academy of Medicine was delivered on Thursday evening, by Dr. GEISCOM, at the lecture room, Clinton Hall. The exercises were commenced with prayer by Rev. Dr. FERRIS.

headline.main: THREE DAYS LATER FROM EUROPE.; MISCELLANEOUS AND GENERAL NEWS. Consols 94 5-8--Cotton Less Firm. FURTHER RISE IN FLOUR AND GRAIN. PARTICULARS FROM THE SEAT OF WAR NO IMPORTANT WAR NEWS. ARRIVAL OF THE ARABIA.

docs.lead_paragraph: The mail stcomer Arabia, from Liverpool, 10 o'clock on morning of Saturday, the 21st ult., arrived at this port early yesterday morning. There is nothing very definite from the Crimea. The allies were to being the siege at all points on the 10th or 12th inst., Nevertheless, speculators were busy in circulating a report that the place had, already fallen.

docs.lead_paragraph: One of our cotemporaries comes into possession of the fact that about one hundred hogs died from suffocation on the Erie Railroad train on Thursday, and that they were purchased by a dealer near Newburg at a dollar a head, and dressed for this market.

docs.lead_paragraph: Rev. W. H. BIDWELL, for many years proprietor and leading Editor of the New-York Evangetist, one of our oldest and ablest religious journals,announces his retirement this week, mainly we regret to see, on account of impaired health.

docs.lead_paragraph: Dr. SKENIER, ot Lmokprot--a venerable and much respected cilizen-died on Monday 1:st of cholera, supposed to have been induced by eatilig oysters. From the Boston Traveller, Nov. 1. DEATH OF LORDI) DENMA.N.
